It's just easier.

00:23:51.170 --> 00:23:54.060
It's that hard
thing you can see.

00:23:54.060 --> 00:23:57.300
It's being made,
it's being done.

00:23:57.300 --> 00:23:58.570
We can play it.

00:23:58.570 --> 00:24:00.760
It means we're probably
doing something right.

00:24:00.760 --> 00:24:03.402
But it's still very difficult
to talk about the people.

00:24:03.402 --> 00:24:05.610
But we saw been talking
about the people a little bit

00:24:05.610 --> 00:24:09.160
here, especially with
accountability in this one.

00:24:09.160 --> 00:24:09.700
It was good.

00:24:09.700 --> 00:24:10.200
Cool.

00:24:12.700 --> 00:24:14.940
So that brings me
to the next topic.

00:24:14.940 --> 00:24:16.699
Teams are composed
of individuals,

00:24:16.699 --> 00:24:18.240
and each person on
your team is going

00:24:18.240 --> 00:24:20.580
to have a lot of different
factors affecting

00:24:20.580 --> 00:24:23.310
what they do, how they
do it, when they do it.

00:24:23.310 --> 00:24:27.350
I can't give you the magic
formula to get them motivated.

00:24:27.350 --> 00:24:30.750
What I can do is show you
some of the different ways

00:24:30.750 --> 00:24:34.120
that you can try to either
understand the people you're

00:24:34.120 --> 00:24:36.400
with, understand the
people on your team,

00:24:36.400 --> 00:24:37.990
or find things to
talk to them about.

00:24:37.990 --> 00:24:40.774
You might notice a
number of these things.

00:24:40.774 --> 00:24:42.190
So to get someone
who's motivated,

00:24:42.190 --> 00:24:45.262
someone who's going to
be able to participate,

00:24:45.262 --> 00:24:46.470
think about all these things.

00:24:46.470 --> 00:24:49.380
Think about personal
development.

00:24:49.380 --> 00:24:51.600
So you're in a
class, you're here

00:24:51.600 --> 00:24:53.300
hopefully because
you want to learn.

00:24:53.300 --> 00:24:55.830
You want to learn a new skill,
you want to try a new skill.

00:24:55.830 --> 00:24:57.330
Everyone wants to
learn a new skill.

00:24:57.330 --> 00:24:59.680
There might be a skill that they
want to work on on your team,

00:24:59.680 --> 00:25:00.570
and I think we've
talked about that

00:25:00.570 --> 00:25:03.330
in the past when we were talking
about the vision statement,

00:25:03.330 --> 00:25:05.970
and people putting down why
they're involved on the team,

00:25:05.970 --> 00:25:07.790
and why they're involved
in this project.

00:25:07.790 --> 00:25:09.873
So being aware of that,
and constantly coming back

00:25:09.873 --> 00:25:12.206
to that for each person,
especially if you have someone

00:25:12.206 --> 00:25:14.110
on your team who is
just not participating,

00:25:14.110 --> 00:25:17.899
and you need to figure
out how to engage them.

00:25:17.899 --> 00:25:19.440
Think about the
skills that they want

00:25:19.440 --> 00:25:20.814
to bring to the
table, the skills

00:25:20.814 --> 00:25:22.170
they're trying to practice.

00:25:22.170 --> 00:25:25.510
When it comes to
motivation, it largely

00:25:25.510 --> 00:25:28.212
comes down to
intrinsic or extrinsic.

00:25:28.212 --> 00:25:30.670
The extrinsic might be the
grade that they're going to get,

00:25:30.670 --> 00:25:35.430
but it's really difficult
to really hone in on that,

00:25:35.430 --> 00:25:37.360
because the grade's
shared between your group.

00:25:37.360 --> 00:25:39.700
So that might not be
the place to look at.

00:25:39.700 --> 00:25:42.480
Try to take a look at
the intrinsic things.

00:25:42.480 --> 00:25:49.060
If they had enthusiasms about
the project at some point,

00:25:49.060 --> 00:25:51.610
try to remember what that was.

00:25:51.610 --> 00:25:54.050
Ask somebody else on your team
what that might have been.

00:25:54.050 --> 00:25:56.250
See if you can bring
that enthusiasm back

00:25:56.250 --> 00:25:57.940
into the project.

00:25:57.940 --> 00:25:59.610
Morale or self-worth.

00:25:59.610 --> 00:26:01.380
There's been some
research that shows

00:26:01.380 --> 00:26:04.180
that the reason why people work
well on teams, and the reason

00:26:04.180 --> 00:26:07.700
why we want to work on teams
is because it brings us

00:26:07.700 --> 00:26:09.764
self-worth.

00:26:09.764 --> 00:26:11.680
And in particular, there's
some self awareness

00:26:11.680 --> 00:26:15.870
that can happen by being
on a team, and getting--

00:26:15.870 --> 00:26:18.570
and actually, it links a little
bit to extrinsic rewards.

00:26:18.570 --> 00:26:22.140
By getting rewarded, getting
feedback on my performance,

00:26:22.140 --> 00:26:24.400
it's going to help me do better.

00:26:24.400 --> 00:26:27.780
Empowerment, giving ownership.

00:26:27.780 --> 00:26:33.551
So raise your hands if your team
uses assigning tasks or taking

00:26:33.551 --> 00:26:34.050
tasks.

00:26:34.050 --> 00:26:36.110
So assigning tasks,
raise your hand.

00:26:36.110 --> 00:26:39.680
If your team assigns
tasks to individuals.

00:26:39.680 --> 00:26:41.110
That team.

00:26:41.110 --> 00:26:42.650
Kind of?

00:26:42.650 --> 00:26:43.830
Yeah.

00:26:43.830 --> 00:26:45.852
You assign, so there's
one person on your team

00:26:45.852 --> 00:26:47.310
that says you are
going to do this.

00:26:50.300 --> 00:26:52.700
Has anybody tried
ownership, where

00:26:52.700 --> 00:26:57.130
someone takes a task from a set
of tasks that are available?

00:26:57.130 --> 00:26:59.330
Little, little.

00:26:59.330 --> 00:27:00.630
When does that work?

00:27:00.630 --> 00:27:02.580
When does ownership work?

00:27:02.580 --> 00:27:04.930
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:04.930 --> 00:27:05.430
What's that?

00:27:05.430 --> 00:27:06.855
AUDIENCE: When people
are eager to work,

00:27:06.855 --> 00:27:08.760
and they're interested
in what we're doing.

00:27:08.760 --> 00:27:10.890
PROFESSOR: So there's some
of those other things.

00:27:10.890 --> 00:27:13.490
There's some enthusiasm over it.

00:27:13.490 --> 00:27:13.990
Yeah?

00:27:13.990 --> 00:27:17.870
AUDIENCE: It's usually a while
before the deadline, too.

00:27:17.870 --> 00:27:19.800
PROFESSOR: OK, cool.

00:27:19.800 --> 00:27:20.300
Yeah?

00:27:20.300 --> 00:27:20.940
AUDIENCE: You can
run into problems

00:27:20.940 --> 00:27:23.660
if you say who's going to do
this, and nobody volunteers.

00:27:23.660 --> 00:27:26.264
So my experience has
been that it's good

00:27:26.264 --> 00:27:28.429
if people can volunteer
for tasks that they're

00:27:28.429 --> 00:27:31.018
enthusiastic about, but then,
if nobody will volunteer

00:27:31.018 --> 00:27:33.559
to do something that needs to
be done, someone has to step up

00:27:33.559 --> 00:27:35.100
and say, OK, you're
going to do this.

00:27:35.100 --> 00:27:36.851
So it's like kind of
a hybrid [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:36.851 --> 00:27:38.600
PROFESSOR: So where
does-- yeah, go ahead.

00:27:38.600 --> 00:27:39.982
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
and I think also,

00:27:39.982 --> 00:27:42.402
it depends on if
everyone on a team

00:27:42.402 --> 00:27:45.306
is willing to take ownership
versus, like, only some people.

00:27:45.306 --> 00:27:48.040
Because that'll create
a different dynamic.

00:27:48.040 --> 00:27:50.248
There's some people who are
really taking initiative,

00:27:50.248 --> 00:27:52.081
but the others aren't,
so you're still going

00:27:52.081 --> 00:27:53.650
to need to assign them tasks.

00:27:53.650 --> 00:27:55.941
So I think something
that's where

00:27:55.941 --> 00:27:58.024
at the beginning ask for
people to take ownership,

00:27:58.024 --> 00:27:59.968
and then the tasks
that are left,

00:27:59.968 --> 00:28:03.880
there's one person who's
going to delegate this out.

00:28:03.880 --> 00:28:06.330
PROFESSOR: So at the beginning,
everybody takes on tasks.

00:28:06.330 --> 00:28:08.440
And at the end, when
you have the leftovers,

00:28:08.440 --> 00:28:09.440
they get assigned.

00:28:09.440 --> 00:28:09.940
Yeah, Matt?

00:28:09.940 --> 00:28:11.912
AUDIENCE: One of
the biggest problems

00:28:11.912 --> 00:28:15.363
I've seen with this is
when you're not thinking

00:28:15.363 --> 00:28:16.842
about the game you
are working on,

00:28:16.842 --> 00:28:19.320
especially this is
very easy since we have

00:28:19.320 --> 00:28:22.562
a lot of other work, then things
can stall, because you're not

00:28:22.562 --> 00:28:23.936
thinking about
what kind of game,

00:28:23.936 --> 00:28:25.727
so you're not thinking
about being passive.

00:28:27.994 --> 00:28:30.160
PROFESSOR: So you might not
actually have ownership.

00:28:30.160 --> 00:28:31.870
It might look like
you had ownership.

00:28:31.870 --> 00:28:33.286
There is the
evidence of ownership

00:28:33.286 --> 00:28:35.500
in that someone said,
OK, I'll take that task.

00:28:35.500 --> 00:28:38.950
But there's no follow through,
there's no commitment.

00:28:38.950 --> 00:28:42.260
And that gets to the
next one, commitment.

00:28:42.260 --> 00:28:45.940
The best way to have commitment
on your team is for one person

00:28:45.940 --> 00:28:48.800
to be committed to
express that commitment,

00:28:48.800 --> 00:28:50.240
to express that loyalty.

00:28:50.240 --> 00:28:51.990
For everyone else
to see that loyalty

00:28:51.990 --> 00:28:53.420
and see that
commitment, and then

00:28:53.420 --> 00:28:55.670
hopefully they pick up the
ball, and they're like, OK,

00:28:55.670 --> 00:28:57.130
I'm going to be committed, too.

00:28:57.130 --> 00:28:59.980
If that second person
doesn't do that, pick it up,

00:28:59.980 --> 00:29:01.810
then it doesn't travel
through the chain,

00:29:01.810 --> 00:29:03.530
it just doesn't happen.

00:29:03.530 --> 00:29:05.030
Even though that
one person went out

00:29:05.030 --> 00:29:06.760
of their way to show
that kind of sacrifice,

00:29:06.760 --> 00:29:07.968
it just didn't get picked up.

00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:13.560
Do see that chain
happening on your teams,

00:29:13.560 --> 00:29:14.764
do you see it breaking?

00:29:14.764 --> 00:29:16.680
Can you identify where
that breaking point is,

00:29:16.680 --> 00:29:20.880
and can you think
about ways to fix that?

00:29:20.880 --> 00:29:24.010
Trust is a big one.

00:29:24.010 --> 00:29:26.750
So raise your hands
if you have worked

00:29:26.750 --> 00:29:28.720
with the majority of
people on your team

00:29:28.720 --> 00:29:31.294
before, in some fashion.

00:29:31.294 --> 00:29:32.460
This class or other classes.

00:29:32.460 --> 00:29:34.407
You feel like you
know your teammates.

00:29:34.407 --> 00:29:36.240
Raise your hands if you
feel like you really

00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:38.406
know your teammates, you've
worked with them before.

00:29:38.406 --> 00:29:40.680
High if you really think so.

00:29:40.680 --> 00:29:43.640
So one, two, maybe.

00:29:43.640 --> 00:29:46.470
One, two, three.

00:29:46.470 --> 00:29:49.326
So think about how well
you know each other,

00:29:49.326 --> 00:29:50.950
think about ways you
can figure out how

00:29:50.950 --> 00:29:53.490
you can know each other better.

00:29:53.490 --> 00:29:55.870
Social interactions.

00:29:55.870 --> 00:29:58.370
Going out for coffee, going out
for lunch, things like that.

00:29:58.370 --> 00:30:00.930
Is there something that
you can do that will

00:30:00.930 --> 00:30:03.140
help that kind of thing happen?

00:30:03.140 --> 00:30:06.600
And then here's the big one,
this is the MIT one, stress.

00:30:06.600 --> 00:30:08.240
Stress tends to be the negative.

00:30:08.240 --> 00:30:11.570
It can be positive, in that
it's the end of the project,

00:30:11.570 --> 00:30:14.390
and it's due, and you just
need to get things done,

00:30:14.390 --> 00:30:16.050
and that could lead to crunch.

00:30:16.050 --> 00:30:18.425
But then there's also the huge
negative aspect of stress,

00:30:18.425 --> 00:30:21.390
and that's very much an external
factor, for the most part.

00:30:21.390 --> 00:30:24.150
It could be in an
internal factor.

00:30:24.150 --> 00:30:27.330
If there's some stress being
caused by internal things

00:30:27.330 --> 00:30:29.200
going on with your team,
it's likely related

00:30:29.200 --> 00:30:30.366
to one of the ones above it.

00:30:33.690 --> 00:30:38.830
So one way to think
about these 7 things,

00:30:38.830 --> 00:30:41.450
you can think of them in
terms of the desirability

00:30:41.450 --> 00:30:44.754
to learn new skills, or the
desirability to take on task.

00:30:44.754 --> 00:30:46.670
So if you're trying to
come up with strategies

00:30:46.670 --> 00:30:49.250
with your team on how to
solve some of these problems,

00:30:49.250 --> 00:30:50.541
think of it in those two terms.

