00:34:55.610 --> 00:34:57.260
as a group.

00:34:57.260 --> 00:34:59.730
What do we mean by one team?

00:34:59.730 --> 00:35:03.085
That the group first
identifies as a team,

00:35:03.085 --> 00:35:04.460
like what we talked
about before.

00:35:04.460 --> 00:35:06.920
They all have a goal that
they're going towards,

00:35:06.920 --> 00:35:09.710
they all identify as
going towards that goal.

00:35:09.710 --> 00:35:13.870
They don't identify as
just an individual group.

00:35:13.870 --> 00:35:18.130
But that's actually a major
part of their identity.

00:35:18.130 --> 00:35:21.890
For them, it's because that's
their 40 hour, 80 hour, 120

00:35:21.890 --> 00:35:26.094
hour work weeks.

00:35:26.094 --> 00:35:27.510
Something I think
you you're going

00:35:27.510 --> 00:35:29.860
to have an issue with,
because you're working

00:35:29.860 --> 00:35:31.690
smaller periods of time.

00:35:31.690 --> 00:35:33.669
But the way they're able
to do that is they've

00:35:33.669 --> 00:35:35.210
got these frequent
team interactions.

00:35:35.210 --> 00:35:36.660
And actually, when
they're working

00:35:36.660 --> 00:35:38.720
for a long period
of time, there are

00:35:38.720 --> 00:35:40.604
people who are
working on their own

00:35:40.604 --> 00:35:42.020
in their home or
their home office

00:35:42.020 --> 00:35:45.070
with another team
that's very far away.

00:35:45.070 --> 00:35:48.090
And yet, these teams
still do a daily stand up.

00:35:48.090 --> 00:35:50.540
Does anybody here do a daily
stand up on their teams

00:35:50.540 --> 00:35:51.040
right now?

00:35:53.670 --> 00:35:56.669
So what they're doing is
they're going on video,

00:35:56.669 --> 00:35:59.210
they're talking to each other
for a very short period of time

00:35:59.210 --> 00:36:01.530
about what they've done,
what they're going to do,

00:36:01.530 --> 00:36:03.711
what's in their way.

00:36:03.711 --> 00:36:05.210
The cool thing with
daily stand ups,

00:36:05.210 --> 00:36:08.130
and why they think
this works for them,

00:36:08.130 --> 00:36:10.190
it goes back to
those seven items

00:36:10.190 --> 00:36:13.250
I listed about how you get
people engaged on a team?

00:36:13.250 --> 00:36:14.950
It shows commitment.

00:36:14.950 --> 00:36:18.650
The fact that there are people
who are showing up to meetings.

00:36:18.650 --> 00:36:20.700
There's some kind of
personal sacrifice.

00:36:20.700 --> 00:36:23.510
Some people are meeting at a
very strange hour of the day

00:36:23.510 --> 00:36:25.199
that they're not
normally going to meet,

00:36:25.199 --> 00:36:26.990
and they're doing that
because of the team.

00:36:26.990 --> 00:36:30.280
They're sacrificing something
personal for the team.

00:36:30.280 --> 00:36:32.090
Everyone else on the
team sees that, they

00:36:32.090 --> 00:36:34.040
see that kind of commitment.

00:36:34.040 --> 00:36:37.120
They feel like they need to
reflect that back themselves.

00:36:37.120 --> 00:36:38.270
Also trust.

00:36:38.270 --> 00:36:39.750
And in this
particular case, it's

00:36:39.750 --> 00:36:42.020
the trust of not letting
meetings take too long.

00:36:42.020 --> 00:36:45.090
These daily stand ups really
should only take 10 minutes.

00:36:45.090 --> 00:36:47.315
An effective team
can do it in five.

00:36:47.315 --> 00:36:49.330
An effective 10 person team.

00:36:49.330 --> 00:36:52.100
30 seconds each, go, everyone
says what they've done.

00:36:52.100 --> 00:36:53.482
Everyone sees each
other's faces.

00:36:53.482 --> 00:36:55.440
The great thing about
seeing each other's faces

00:36:55.440 --> 00:36:59.211
is you can see what stage of
fear and anxiety they're in.

00:36:59.211 --> 00:37:00.710
And you can then
talk to them later,

00:37:00.710 --> 00:37:02.876
and have some other personal
interactions with them.

00:37:05.350 --> 00:37:08.926
The other thing they do,
they do co-located work.

00:37:08.926 --> 00:37:10.550
They've got money
sometimes, so they're

00:37:10.550 --> 00:37:12.185
flying people back and forth.

00:37:12.185 --> 00:37:14.060
But again, they're also
doing co-located work

00:37:14.060 --> 00:37:17.270
by doing things, having Skype
always on in the background

00:37:17.270 --> 00:37:18.630
while they're working together.

00:37:18.630 --> 00:37:20.338
But they're not doing
it the entire time,

00:37:20.338 --> 00:37:21.790
they can't afford that.

00:37:21.790 --> 00:37:27.025
So one thing you can do is to
schedule your co-located time

00:37:27.025 --> 00:37:29.150
at the beginning of the
project, which is basically

00:37:29.150 --> 00:37:32.600
what we've been doing in
class for the past few weeks.

00:37:32.600 --> 00:37:35.070
Identifying important
milestones, and making sure

00:37:35.070 --> 00:37:38.090
you've scheduled a co-located
period during that milestone,

00:37:38.090 --> 00:37:40.630
right before that milestone
is going to help you greatly.

00:37:40.630 --> 00:37:42.888
Doing insert teams,
and doing video chat.

00:37:45.760 --> 00:37:48.360
And here's a big one we haven't
talked about in class so much,

00:37:48.360 --> 00:37:50.550
but I get the impression
that some of you

00:37:50.550 --> 00:37:53.470
might be interested
in this kind of thing.

00:37:53.470 --> 00:37:54.790
Having coaches.

00:37:54.790 --> 00:37:56.970
So we've already seen
some of the teams

00:37:56.970 --> 00:38:00.200
have a dedicated scrum
master or producer.

00:38:00.200 --> 00:38:02.570
Think about having
a dedicated coach.

00:38:02.570 --> 00:38:04.730
So someone who's
on your team, who's

00:38:04.730 --> 00:38:07.100
there to cultivate team spirit.

00:38:07.100 --> 00:38:09.440
They're going to emphasize
the importance of one team.

00:38:09.440 --> 00:38:11.410
They could be your scrum
master or producer,

00:38:11.410 --> 00:38:15.240
but they're not
actually the same role.

00:38:15.240 --> 00:38:19.140
The scrum master or the producer
is measuring productivity.

00:38:19.140 --> 00:38:22.190
They're measuring tasks on
how well things get done.

00:38:22.190 --> 00:38:23.464
The coach is very different.

00:38:23.464 --> 00:38:25.755
They're looking at how people
interact with each other,

00:38:25.755 --> 00:38:27.080
how people talk to each other.

00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:28.570
How people work with each other.

00:38:28.570 --> 00:38:31.600
Oftentimes, people who are
naturally inclined to do one

00:38:31.600 --> 00:38:34.870
can be inclined to do the other,
but that's not always the case.

00:38:34.870 --> 00:38:36.950
So if you have
someone on your team

00:38:36.950 --> 00:38:41.790
who is one of those extroverted,
outgoing, or even introverted

00:38:41.790 --> 00:38:45.010
but really interested in what
individuals do one-on-one,

00:38:45.010 --> 00:38:46.645
and how individuals work.

00:38:46.645 --> 00:38:50.260
See if you can incorporate
some coaching strategies

00:38:50.260 --> 00:38:52.136
with your teammates.

00:38:52.136 --> 00:38:53.885
And again, you can do
one-on-one meetings,

00:38:53.885 --> 00:38:55.500
and we can talk about
this in the future

00:38:55.500 --> 00:38:57.291
if you're interested
in this kind of stuff.

00:38:57.291 --> 00:39:01.820
We can unpack on this topic
and talk about it further.

00:39:01.820 --> 00:39:04.730
But I highly recommend it.

00:39:04.730 --> 00:39:06.640
So I did mention meetings.

00:39:06.640 --> 00:39:08.470
You do have agile
meetings, these people

00:39:08.470 --> 00:39:10.640
have agile meetings.

00:39:10.640 --> 00:39:13.120
These are what they are.

00:39:13.120 --> 00:39:19.360
So who has a formal sprint
process, where you plan

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:21.115
your sprint before you start?

00:39:21.115 --> 00:39:24.890
So you basically create your
sprint task list at a meeting?

00:39:24.890 --> 00:39:26.520
Is everyone there?

00:39:26.520 --> 00:39:28.050
Not everyone's there.

00:39:28.050 --> 00:39:34.420
AUDIENCE: We have the tasks,
and we've focused [INAUDIBLE].

00:39:34.420 --> 00:39:36.952
So we do have a formal
week-by-week, here's

00:39:36.952 --> 00:39:38.410
what we want to
get done this week.

00:39:38.410 --> 00:39:39.900
PROFESSOR: OK, cool.

00:39:39.900 --> 00:39:43.102
And you had a meeting
to create that?

00:39:43.102 --> 00:39:44.560
Then you have your
daily stand ups.

00:39:44.560 --> 00:39:48.144
At the end of the sprint, you
want to have a sprint review.

00:39:48.144 --> 00:39:50.560
Just basically the inverse of
the sprint planning meeting.

00:39:50.560 --> 00:39:52.507
You go back and
see what you made.

00:39:52.507 --> 00:39:54.590
Hopefully, you have a build
and you just basically

00:39:54.590 --> 00:39:58.060
look at the build, compare the
build to the completed tasks,

00:39:58.060 --> 00:39:59.710
and make sure it matches.

00:39:59.710 --> 00:40:02.380
The other meeting that you
may or may not be doing

00:40:02.380 --> 00:40:04.230
is the agile retrospective.

00:40:04.230 --> 00:40:06.220
And that's how did
you work this week?

00:40:06.220 --> 00:40:07.800
Is anybody doing
that, is anybody

00:40:07.800 --> 00:40:09.960
at the end of their
sprint, talking

00:40:09.960 --> 00:40:14.142
about the processes of what
you did and how you did it?

00:40:16.811 --> 00:40:17.310
OK.

00:40:17.310 --> 00:40:19.020
It's what I expect.

00:40:21.150 --> 00:40:22.900
I think you're doing
yourself a disservice

00:40:22.900 --> 00:40:23.941
if you're not doing that.

00:40:23.941 --> 00:40:25.600
And particularly, if
you are doing that

00:40:25.600 --> 00:40:27.650
and you're making that
a face to face meeting,

00:40:27.650 --> 00:40:29.130
that's the time when
you can talk about some

00:40:29.130 --> 00:40:30.500
of these interpersonal issues.

00:40:30.500 --> 00:40:31.875
That's the time
when you can talk

00:40:31.875 --> 00:40:34.650
about your feelings, that's
the time when you can open up,

00:40:34.650 --> 00:40:37.130
and try to figure
out what is about,

00:40:37.130 --> 00:40:40.850
why are some of these
tasks not getting taken on,

00:40:40.850 --> 00:40:44.210
who's not doing them, and what's
in their way from doing them.

00:40:44.210 --> 00:40:48.392
But really, it's not really
about what's in the way,

00:40:48.392 --> 00:40:49.600
it's difficult to talk about.

00:40:49.600 --> 00:40:51.058
It's not about
what's in their way,

00:40:51.058 --> 00:40:52.660
but it might be
about what outside

00:40:52.660 --> 00:40:55.250
of the project and outside of
the team could be in their way?

00:40:55.250 --> 00:40:57.275
And can you work through
some of those issues?

00:41:00.840 --> 00:41:02.976
So I'm done.

00:41:02.976 --> 00:41:05.350
What I'd like you do before
you go and work in your teams

00:41:05.350 --> 00:41:08.240
is schedule a sprint
retrospective.

00:41:08.240 --> 00:41:11.220
So take a look at
your sprint process.

00:41:11.220 --> 00:41:12.220
How long is your sprint?

00:41:12.220 --> 00:41:13.990
Is it one week or two weeks?

00:41:13.990 --> 00:41:18.800
We've been assuming
it's one-week sprints.

00:41:18.800 --> 00:41:21.610
Schedule a time period
that everyone can attend,

00:41:21.610 --> 00:41:24.856
and an amount of time
that they can attend.

00:41:24.856 --> 00:41:26.230
That they can see
each other face

00:41:26.230 --> 00:41:28.542
to face, but not necessarily
are in the same room.

00:41:28.542 --> 00:41:30.250
If they can be in the
same room, awesome.

00:41:30.250 --> 00:41:32.535
If you can't, try
to figure out a time

00:41:32.535 --> 00:41:37.330
that you can chat using Google
Hangout, or some other kind

00:41:37.330 --> 00:41:40.469
of face to face video chat.

00:41:40.469 --> 00:41:42.260
Make sure the meeting
is focused on talking

00:41:42.260 --> 00:41:43.500
about your processes.

00:41:43.500 --> 00:41:46.052
So don't talk about your game,
don't talk about the work

00:41:46.052 --> 00:41:46.760
that you've done.

00:41:46.760 --> 00:41:50.450
Talk about how you
organized yourself.

00:41:50.450 --> 00:41:54.050
And in particular, talk about
your interpersonal matters.

00:41:54.050 --> 00:41:56.530
Basically, communicate
about communicating.

00:41:56.530 --> 00:42:01.280
So talk about how you're
talking to each other.

00:42:01.280 --> 00:42:03.865
And yeah, I want to talk to you
about this again in a couple

00:42:03.865 --> 00:42:04.365
weeks.

00:42:10.750 --> 00:42:12.500
I think most of you
right now are probably

00:42:12.500 --> 00:42:15.200
in the concepting phase,
pre-production phase right now.

00:42:15.200 --> 00:42:16.700
You're still figuring
out your game,

00:42:16.700 --> 00:42:18.762
you haven't quite-- I
guess you guys are actually

00:42:18.762 --> 00:42:20.470
working on your back
end, because someone

00:42:20.470 --> 00:42:22.920
did the initial design for you.

00:42:22.920 --> 00:42:25.540
The rest are probably still
working out the design phase.

00:42:25.540 --> 00:42:27.430
When I talk about
this again, you'll

00:42:27.430 --> 00:42:30.960
likely be in full-on
production mode,

00:42:30.960 --> 00:42:33.830
and so some of the activities
I'm going to show you

00:42:33.830 --> 00:42:38.570
might hopefully help when
you're doing these meetings.

